data.body:
Hello

It looks like the GamepadInputCollection.AddGlobalDevices method has a bug in it when the player's gamepad is not the first device. It stops looking for devices after the first missing device, so if my gamepad is device 2 and nothing is plugged in on device one, I'll have no valid gamepads:(

Suggest something like the following instead, where the number of supported devices is either hard coded, or exposed as user or application data:

```
public void AddGlobalDevices()
{
    for (var i = 0; i < MaxSupportedDevices; i++)
    {
        GlobalGamepadInputSource gamepad = new GlobalGamepadInputSource(i);
        gamepad.UpdateState();
        if (!gamepad.IsAvailable) continue;

        this.AddSource(gamepad);
    }
}
```

As you probably all know, C# supports its own kind of union type by using [explicit memory layouts](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.runtime.interopservices.structlayoutattribute%28v=vs.100%29.aspx) in structs. This would basically allow to define the following:

```
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit)]
public struct Vector3
{
    // Regular field access
    [FieldOffset(0)]
    public float X;
    [FieldOffset(4)]
    public float Y;
    [FieldOffset(8)]
    public float Z;

    // Convenience access
    [FieldOffset(0)]
    public Vector2 XY;
}
```

So basically replacing the `Xy` Property with a direct data access using explicit struct layouts, which would likely yield a small performance benefit when doing CPU-heavy batch operations involving this. Fields are also a little bit more flexible when it comes to out / ref usage and absolutely no functionality would be lost.

All in all, it appears that there is no good reason not to do this. Will likely change in conjunction with the [OpenTK upgrade](https://github.com/AdamsLair/duality/issues/160), so breaking changes are reduced to a minimum.

And while we're at breaking stuff anyway, this could also be a good opportunity to finally move all of this Vector math stuff out of OpenTK and into a distinct library, so Farseer and Duality can use it without depending on OpenTK, which kind of has a different purpose than defining vector math.

Just some wild thoughts. Feedback welcome.
